<DOC><DOCNO> AP890712-0202 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1839EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-12 0425</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0435</SECOND><HEAD>Widely Scattered Thunderstorms, Heat Waves Continue</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms developed Wednesday over parts of the Plains, theMidwest and the Appalachians, and in the West, and a heat wavecontinued over North Carolina and the middle Mississippi Valley.   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain from the central andsouthern Appalachians across the Tennessee Valley, from sections ofMissouri and Arkansas to northern Oklahoma, and in parts of Iowa.   Heaviest rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was 1.83inches at Ottumwa, Iowa.   One to 2 inches of rain fell within an hour in the Appalachiansof southeastern Kentucky, southwestern Virginia and northeasternTennessee.   Thunderstorms also were widespread across the Rockies and theGreat Basin area of Nevada and western Utah, with a possibility oflocally heavy rain.   More showers and thunderstorms were scattered across much of theOhio Valley and the lower Great Lakes region. An isolated severethunderstorm produced a tornado near Marion, Ohio.   Thunderstorms rumbled over sections of Virginia and theCarolinas, producing wind gusts to 50 mph in Tyrrell County, N.C.   And temperatures in North Carolina surged toward 100 degrees forthe fifth consecutive day. By 1 p.m., Cherry Point had already hit100. At 11 a.m., a temperature of 95 and 58 percent humidityproduced a heat index of 113 at the New River Marine Base.   St. Louis, Mo., had its ninth day of temperatures in the 90s. Theheat there has been blamed for three deaths. During a heat warninglast month, at least five deaths were blamed on the heat. At thistime last year, said the Missouri Department of Health, there were25 heat-related deaths.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57degrees along the California coast at Crescent City, San Simeon,Arcata and Hayward to 104 in at Palm Springs, Calif. Wednesday's lowin the Lower 48 states was 35 in the California Sierras, at Truckee.   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom the northern and central Rockies across sections of the greatPlains, Arkansas and the Tennessee Valley to the East Coast states.Widely scattered thunderstorms were forecast over the central GulfCoast states and along the Texas Coast.   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;in the 70s from New England to the Great Lakes region, and insections of the northern and central Rockies; over 100 in the desertSouthwest, and in sections of south-central and southwestern Texas;and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>